 on both his humanist education, particularly his reading of Xenophon's Cyropaedia, and his kingship in Scotland, James developed a clear, considered agenda for crown finance. He used it consciously to underwrite his novel position as the first king of "Great Britain" and to consolidate the Stuart dynastyoutside of Scotland. This study analyses in detail how James fashioned and refashioned political regimes in England to further this agenda between 1603-25. JOHN CRAMSIE is Assistant Professor of British and Irish Historyat Union College, Schenectady, New York.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFinance, PubliczGreat BritainxHistoryyTo 1688. 0aMonarchyzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh1 aCramsie, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846150982?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846150982423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846150982/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles